Claim 1 — System Claim:
A computer-implemented system for secure academic examination management comprising:
(a) a blockchain smart contract configured to store IPFS content identifiers (CIDs) of encrypted examination content and corresponding cryptographic unlock timestamps, and to enforce temporal access control by comparing a blockchain consensus timestamp (block.timestamp) against said stored unlock timestamp, wherein temporal manipulation requires 51% network consensus;
(b) a dual-layer hybrid encryption module comprising: (i) AES-256-CBC symmetric encryption with a randomly generated 256-bit key and 128-bit initialization vector for encrypting examination content, and (ii) RSA-2048-OAEP asymmetric encryption for encrypting and protecting the AES encryption key;
(c) a distributed content-addressed storage system (IPFS) for storing encrypted examination bundles, wherein the content identifier (CID) is derived as a SHA-256 hash of the stored content, and CIDs are anchored to the blockchain to create dual-layer immutability verification;
(d) a student response recording mechanism using cryptographic wallet signatures (secp256k1 ECC via MetaMask) that creates a non-repudiable, blockchain-timestamped record of examination submission attributable to the student's wallet address;
(e) an immutable grade recording mechanism that permanently records examination scores on the blockchain in an append-only structure, resistant to modification by any party including the contract deployer.

Claim 2 — Method Claim:
A method for securing academic examination delivery comprising:
encrypting examination content using AES-256-CBC with a randomly generated 256-bit symmetric key and 128-bit initialization vector;
encrypting said symmetric key using RSA-2048-OAEP asymmetric encryption;
bundling the encrypted content, encrypted key, and IV; uploading the bundle to IPFS; and recording the resulting content-addressed identifier (CID) and a future unlock timestamp on a blockchain via a smart contract;
enforcing temporal access control by validating a blockchain consensus timestamp (block.timestamp) against the stored unlock timestamp at the protocol level, preventing any administrator from bypassing the time-lock;
recording student examination responses as cryptographically wallet-signed IPFS content references on the blockchain, providing non-repudiable proof of submission identity and time; and
recording student grades as immutable append-only blockchain entries, permanently preventing modification.

Claim 3 — Novelty/Differentiation Claim:
The system of Claim 1, wherein the temporal access control is enforced exclusively at the blockchain consensus layer using block.timestamp, not at the application layer, smart contract logic layer, or server time layer, such that bypassing the time-lock requires overcoming 51% of total network validation power, rendering it economically and practically infeasible.

